# BimRoss: slack-orchestrator routing tiers (`tool_id` / `Kind`)

Use this when changing **how** `slack-orchestrator` classifies messages for `routing.Decision` (NATS targets, admin/orchestrator debug UI). Implementation lives under **`slack-orchestrator/internal/routing/`** (`decide.go`, **`tools.go`**).

## Tier 0 — Structural triggers (no text semantics)

Handled in **`Decide`** / broadcast classification **before** tool vs conversation:

- `<!everyone>` / `<!here>` / `@here`-style broadcast → fanout, **`KindConversation`** for the broadcast branch.
- `<!channel>` / `@channel` → capped fanout, **`KindConversation`**.
- Explicit squad **`@mention`** of bot users → mention trigger; may combine with Tier 1.
- Plain thread follow-up uses **`ThreadPlainHandoffKey`** (last squad mention in thread) for single-target routing.

Do not replace Tier 0 with LLM calls.

## Tier 1 — Explicit tool name only (`ClassifyToolOrConversation`)

**`ClassifyToolOrConversation`** in **`tools.go`** must match **only** when the user **names the canonical skill id** in natural text:

- Hyphenated ids split into segments; allow **spaces, hyphens, or underscores** between segments (case-insensitive), e.g. `read-company`, `read company`, `read_company`.
- Strip Slack angle tokens (`<@…>`, `<!…>`, `<#…>`) before matching so `<@UGARTH> read-twitter` works.

**Do not** add Tier 1 “intent” shortcuts such as:

- loose substrings: `onboard`, `create channel`, `search twitter for …`, `company digest`
- synonym lists for paraphrases (that belongs in **Tier 2**, not `tools.go`)

If no Tier 1 match → **`KindConversation`** (empty `tool_id`). That is intentional: casual chat must not get a false **`KindTool`** stamp.

### Catalog sync

- **`tier1PatternEntries`** in **`tools.go`** must include canonical skill **`id`** values from **`slack-orchestrator/internal/inbound.DefaultCapabilityContractV1`** (`Skills[].ID`) **if** they should be Tier-1 invocable by name. Add **legacy `write-*` pattern rows** that normalize to **`create-*`** when mutating skills were renamed, so explicit user phrasing stays stable.
- New ids should be **multi-segment** (`foo-bar-baz`); the pattern builder splits on `-`.

## Tier 2 — Fuzzy / paraphrase routing (future)

Reserved for a **separate** path (small model, embeddings, or LLM) that outputs the **same** `routing.Decision` schema — **not** ad hoc keyword lists in **`tools.go`**. Until that exists, unmatched text stays conversation-only at the orchestrator layer.

## Relationship to workers (`employee-factory`)

Orchestrator **`tool_id`** is **dispatch + observability**. **`employee-factory`** still enforces **assigned skills**, owner hints, and thread rules — see **`slack-deterministic-tool-routing-contract.mdc`**. A **`KindTool`** decision does not mean every targeted pod executes that runtime tool.

**Paraphrase and fuzzy intent** should **not** be solved by stuffing **`tools.go`** with synonyms. At the worker, prefer a **small** deterministic surface (explicit names + catalog aliases) plus the **capability router LLM** for scalable NL→`tool_intent` when Tier 1 did not fire—see **`slack-deterministic-tool-routing-contract.mdc`** (“Worker: keep keyword matching minimal”) and **`bimross-skill-factory-checklist.mdc`**. Until a dedicated orchestrator Tier-2 exists, that router LLM is the practical Tier-2-like layer.

## Tests

- **`internal/routing/tools_test.go`** — Tier 1 positive/negative cases (explicit name vs “onboard” / keyword search).
- **`internal/routing/routing_test.go`** — **`Decide`** integration: mention + tool uses messages that include an **explicit** Tier 1 phrase when **`KindTool`** is expected.

When changing Tier 1 behavior, update both.

